Birthday


Happy 1st Birthday Son! 

Friday, December 11, 2015







11th
December 2014, Thursday. Me & my wife have never thought that
this is the day which is going to change our life, forever. The day
which turned out to be the most memorable day of our life. I remember
that morning when we visited the doctor and he happily surprised us
by saying that, “Today is the day!”. I was feeling more fear than
my wife, but I was acting opposite. 

I still remember pace of my
heart, jumping like a fish in water, when my wife was taken inside to
do the honors. However, the situation was more tensed outside, as if
India vs Pakistan cricket match reached to final over stage.
Suddenly, I heard a cute sound of crying inside. Yes, the match was
won, a baby boy was born!




Today,
the boy is turning 1. I always cherish the moment when I took him in
my arms for very first time and I felt “complete”. It has been
the most lively year of my life. Most of our conversations have been
non-verbal of course, but trust me; it’s the most beautiful ever. 

He makes me laugh when I’m sad. He makes me feel special when I
felt I’m not good enough. He probably understands me more than
anyone else. Every day, I eagerly wait for the moment when I reach
home and he runs towards me as soon as he sees me. And that half or a
minute of action is beyond words.




On
his 1st
birthday, I would also like to thank my wife for giving me such
precious gem. Thanks for bearing all the pain while you were
pregnant. Thanks for sharing sleepless nights. Thanks for running to
him when he cries. Thanks for being there with him whenever I can’t.




The
world is definitely a good place to live in. Education has taken
better approach. Freedom of speech has equal importance.
Opportunities are infinite. Laughter is far often heard. Love exists.
Relation matters. And, most importantly, humanity is still alive.




I
would not like to portray anything negative over here, because life
is full of positive things to focus into. I wish every human being
emphasizes more on ‘being human’ and so as my child. On his very
1st
birthday, I promise to support him in every course of life. I promise
to give him better education. I promise to provide him healthy &
competitive environment to grow. I promise to be a good father.




Happy
1st Birthday Son!














featured


A Reservation Dream

Saturday, October 03, 2015









" There is no caste in blood." - Edwin Arnold

And, finally, a weekend arrived. It was a purposeful Saturday morning. The purpose was to spend quality time with family. The plan was set. A movie followed with a buffet lunch at city’s premium restaurant.

After waiting in queue at ticket window for long time, I’ve got my turn. To a bit of my surprise, the person at the window asked me, “What’s your caste, Sir?”. I didn’t get it at first. I thought listening to boss’s loud lectures and customer’s rude complaints everyday has brought me a hearing problem. So, I modestly said, “Sorry, I didn’t get you.” He repeated, “What’s your caste, Sir?” This time I heard it right. I thought that it might be a kind of survey by our government to see which caste views which actors’ movies the most, so that it would be easier for them to give election tickets to those actors in next election. I answered him. He politely said, “Sorry Sir, we only have one ticket reserved for your caste.” Till the time I realize what he said, I had been pushed out of the queue. Lately, I understood what he said but had no clue ‘why’.

Being a middle class family, we can’t afford to waste our time in thinking more about it, as we rarely get such time to spend with family. So, we decided to continue with our plan and reached the premium restaurant we always wanted to visit. And, to all of our surprise, the story repeated. There was a separate waiting list for different castes and we’ve been asked to wait for at least couple of hours to get a table which is suitable to our caste. I was upset. I found it totally disgusting. Till the time we understand the whole disturbing situation, I started hearing an alarm sound. And, to my great relief, it was morning alarm. What I saw was actually a dream. An unwanted dream.

“We’ve got a reservation”, a statement which is widely being used by Reserved category people to refer their scope (or rather rights) of getting admission in education institutes, however General category people use this to refer their either bus or train reservation. Reservation was introduced in the system at the time of era of untouchability, when the difference between earnings of rich & poor people was too big and poor people were not able to grow or even survive due to low education. The core intention was to provide equal rights to all, however nowadays it is being used (read misused here) by all those who actually are in no need of this special service.

The time has changed. In current trends, being in reserved category is such a privilege that everybody wants to be there. Wealthy and forward people have no issue in being known as ‘backwards’, rather they would be more than happy if government allows them to be so. Reservation word has started sounding like US Visa, everybody wants it, no matter how. The saddest thing is, this movement relatively affects the people who’re in actual need of this.

The constitution of country needs to be changed, not by adding more castes in OBCs, but by thinking about disposal of the whole reservation system. And, if it still needs to be there then it should purely be based on poverty line and should not be based on castes. Each caste is producing doctors and engineers nowadays. The castes which were backwards at the time of independence are very much wealthy nowadays. Moreover, there is also a large pool of poor people in General category, which neither gets an admission anywhere even though scoring high marks nor their families get any privileges. Nowadays, where government is busy in promoting ‘Skill India’, this diseased group of people is promoting ‘Reservation India’.

It’s the time to scrap the discrimination. It’s the time to decide whether ‘No Reservation’ or ‘Reservation for only Needy”. Otherwise, we’re not far away from the dream I saw above, when hospitals will also start taking admission based on castes. Petrol stations will also have a special queue for this low fuel people. Prices of vegetables will also be lower for them. All lower berths in train compartments will be allocated to them. Indian Cricket Team will also have 2 SCs, 3 STs, 6 OBCs and 1 General for 12th man. ATM machine will start giving 200 Rs when they request for 100 Rs, in which 50 Rs will be deducted from our account and government will contribute the rest 50 Rs. And, the most crucial one, girls will only marry those ‘privileged’ boys.

Let's stop PRESERVATION of RESERVATION !!!















About me

 Hey, I'm Niraj Shah. Welcome to my web world! I'm an Electronics Engineer by education, a Delivery Manager in an IT organization by profession and an informal writer by passion. I would like to pen down my thoughts on almost anything, anytime, anywhere. I would love to spend time with my family which truly defines meaning of 'life' for me. I would also like to read as much as possible as it helps me to nurture my inner self. I'm very much fond of animation movies too, which activates my dreamland cells. I'm a firm believer of 'karma' and consider it more than religion. Stay Happy, Stay Healthy!   














